Introduction

There are a few different packages for simulating colorblindness but my personal favorite at the moment is colorblindr. Unlike colorblindness which is a good alternative, colorblindr also shows you tritanopia or blue-yellow colorblindness. That feature makes it worth some of the pain-in-the butt additional code you have to do below.

The examples below use version 0.1.0 and there is also a walkthrough available from the authors.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this walkthrough you will see code and examples so that you should be able to:

  • Use cvd_grid() to simulate colorblindness and grayscale versions of your plot
  • Install packages from gitub using the remotes package
  • Turn your base R plots into grobs using as.grob() from ggplotify
  • Explain why the default ggplot2 colorscheme is bad
  • Pick colorblind friendly palettes

Install and Load Packages

Unfortunately, colorblindr is not on the CRAN server, it is on github. Use the install_github() function from the remotes packages to install this and its dependencies (cowplot and colorspace).

install.packages("remotes")
remotes::install_github("wilkelab/cowplot")
install.packages("colorspace", repos = "http://R-Forge.R-project.org")
remotes::install_github("clauswilke/colorblindr")

For simulating on base R plots instead of ggplots, well need an extra package, ggplotify.

install.packages("ggplotify")

And then, dont forget to load your packages, including ggplot2!

library(colorblindr)
library(ggplotify)
library(ggplot2)

Simulate Colorblindness with ggplot2

To start, Im going to create some a basic ggplot graphics for demonstration purposes, using the iris dataset.

plot1 <- ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, col = Species)) + 
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

Now lets take a look at it. I like this package because it makes it very easy, using a color vision deficiency or CVD simulator function to show you the most common deficiencies and what the plot would look like in grayscale.

cvd_grid(plot1)

Simulate Colorblindness with base R

Unfortunately, the regular cvd_grid() function doesnt work with base R plots, e.g.those made using plot() or hist(). But there are a few workarounds. The shortest Ive found is to turn your plot into a grob object, using as.grob() from the ggplotify package to make it readable.

bad.col <- c("red", "green", "orange")
plot3 <- as.grob(~plot(iris$Sepal.Length,  iris$Sepal.Width, col = bad.col[factor(iris$Species)], pch=16))

cvd_grid(plot3)

A few weird code points. You have to use ~ in front of your plot code, and you cant call out the plot early, name it, and then continue on.

Turns out that once you use the plot() function, it changes it into a class NULL object and that breaks as.grob()s brains all the way into gooey component pieces. So the following versions will not convert to a ggplot object and will not work. You can try them though, if you dont believe me!

wtf <- plot(iris$Sepal.Length,  iris$Sepal.Width, col = bad.col[factor(iris$Species)])
as.grob(wtf)
as.grob(~wtf)
as.grob(expression(wtf))

Why Meaghan Hates The Default Color Scheme

And now we get to the meat of this post, the juicy nitpicking rage. Yes, the default ggplot2 colorscheme is pretty. I can appreciate the greatness of a rainbow, I grew up in the era of technicolor acid-drop Lisa Frank trapper keepers, but this color scheme is different. It is a rainbow of lies and is only pretty the same way an oilspill is.

Dont worry, I have evidence to support my thesis. First, lets make some fake data with plenty of groups.

x <- rnorm(n = 200, mean = 50, sd = 7)
y <- rnorm(n = 200, mean = 40, sd = 7)
group.letters <- sample(c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E", "F", "G", "H", "I", "J", "K"),size = 200, replace = TRUE)
fake.data <- data.frame(x, y, group.letters)
smol.fake.data <- subset(fake.data, group.letters %in% c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E", "F"))

Now, lets make a scatterplot, using all those groups as the color variables. Thats 11 groups, which is a lot, and leads us to my first point: the default scheme is bad even if you have good color vision.

start.plot <- ggplot(fake.data, aes(x = x, y = y, col = group.letters)) + geom_point(size = 3)

start.plot

Can you tell the difference between F and G? Next to each other, maybe, but I dare you to figure out which one is which on the plot.Find one or two youre super confident about, then look at this labelled plot of them.

start.plot + geom_text(label = group.letters, col = "black", nudge_x = .5, nudge_y = .5)

Dont lie to yourself - you know that was an impossible challenge. It shouldnt take you 5 minutes to identify a single dot! And once you get past about 6 categories, the default color scheme is pretty hard to read even if you have super awesome color vision.

Which brings me to point 2, as demonstrated by colorblindr: if you dont have awesome color vision, the default scheme is even worse! That means if youre colorblind or printing things out in grayscale (you ancient, decrepit tree destroyer you), then this is what you get:

cvd_grid(start.plot)

But Meaghan, What Palettes Should I Use?

There are so, so many! The issue were looking at here is relying overly much on hue of a color to convey meaning. But color isnt just red or green. Its dark red, light green, desaturated orange, etc. Play around with value (how dark or light it is) and saturation (how much grey is in it) and youll be able to overcome these issues.

less.bad.col <- c("red3", "darkgreen", "orange")
cvd_grid(as.grob(~plot(iris$Sepal.Length,  iris$Sepal.Width, col = less.bad.col[factor(iris$Species)], pch=16)))

Also, there are many other palettes! For example, ggplot2 now has the viridis color scheme embedded in it. Which still is rough for an 11 group palette, but works fine for versions with fewer groups.

ggplot(smol.fake.data, 
       aes(x = x, y = y, col = group.letters)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3)+ 
  scale_color_viridis_d()

And the colorblindR package comes with its own helpful little palette for up to 8 groups, OkabeIto.

ggplot(smol.fake.data, 
       aes(x = x, y = y, col = group.letters)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3)+
  scale_color_OkabeIto()

R comes with quite a few different palettes that should be easy to use, including diverging and sequential palettes. You can access a list of these using palette.pals() for qualitative color schemes and hcl.pals() for sequential or diverging palettes. Then, you can create a list of colors using either palette.colors() or hcl.colors(), setting the palette you want and the number of colors you need.

hcl.pals()
palette.pals()

new.col <- hcl.colors(n = 11, palette = "Green-Yellow" )
qual.col <- palette.colors(n = 11, palette = "Paired" )

And lets not forget that you dont have to use just color! You can change shapes, you can change point sizes, you can facet out by group, or you could combine categories! Just please, please, dont use the default color palette.
